Backlog section: Tests.

## Context

PR #77 added three new tests in `packages/api/src/__tests__/error-handler.test.ts` that each repeat the same setup:

```ts
const logSpy = vi.spyOn(await import('../middleware/logger.js').then(m => m.logger), 'error');
const app = createTestApp();
// ... define a route ...
app.use(errorHandler);
// ... make a request ...
// ... assert on logSpy.mock.calls[0]?.[0] ...
logSpy.mockRestore();
```

The dynamic import + spyOn + restore lifecycle is repeated verbatim per test. Future tests would copy it again.

## Proposed change

Hoist the spy setup into one of these (editorial — pick the one that reads best in this test file's style):

**Option A — a helper function:**

```ts
async function spyLoggerError() {
  const { logger } = await import('../middleware/logger.js');
  return vi.spyOn(logger, 'error');
}
```

Then each test: `const logSpy = await spyLoggerError(); ... logSpy.mockRestore();`

**Option B — `beforeEach` / `afterEach` lifecycle:**

```ts
let logSpy: ReturnType<typeof vi.spyOn>;
beforeEach(async () => {
  const { logger } = await import('../middleware/logger.js');
  logSpy = vi.spyOn(logger, 'error');
});
afterEach(() => logSpy.mockRestore());
```

Then each test just reads `logSpy.mock.calls[...]`.

Both eliminate the duplication. Option B is the more idiomatic Vitest style; Option A is more explicit about which tests use the spy.

## Out of scope

- Restructuring the existing AppError / status-code tests in the same file — those don't share the duplication.
- Extracting an `errorHandlerTestApp(routes)` helper across the whole file — could come later, larger refactor.

## Acceptance

- `pnpm --filter @sms/api test` passes.
- The three tests touched by #77 (`logs request method and route ...`, `logs the route pattern, not concrete path params ...`, `logs <unrouted> when no route matched ...`) no longer each repeat the dynamic-import-and-spy block.

## References

